Project: Kreuzstich rewrite

A cross-stitch pattern design app, rewrite of https://github.com/polletfa/Kreuzstich. The original is written in C++ with Qt, using a lib+app split. The rewrite will be a monolith (single target) but with clean internal separation between:

    gui — widgets and user interaction
    creator — core logic (yarn database, image processing, pattern)

Technology: C++17, Qt6, CMake, single app target. English UI with German translation from the start (app name stays "Kreuzstich"). Multilingual via Qt translation system (tr(), .ts/.qm files).

Color matching:

    RGB → LAB color space for distance computation
    RGB → XYZ using D65/2° white point
    XYZ → LAB with piecewise f() function (not just pow(1/3))
    Missing: sRGB linearization before matrix multiplication (gamma correction)
    Distance: CIE76 Euclidean distance in LAB space
    Color values come from photos of yarn color cards, processed with ImageMagick

App features discussed:

Pattern view:

    Pixel grid displayed with color numbers
    Rectangle selection tool (ephemeral)
    Highlight a selected color
    Mark pixels as done/not-done (per pixel, stored permanently)
    Dim done pixels

Color/statistics panel (contextual to current area selection):

    List colors present in selected area with stitch counts
    Show done/remaining per color
    Flag rare colors (configurable threshold) as candidates for replacement
    Click color to highlight in pattern view
    Replace one color with another within selection

Work units (area × color, saved temporarily):

    User selects area + colors to work on
    App saves the work unit (rectangle + color list + per-color done status)
    User can generate a batch PDF for the whole area
    When done, mark entire work unit as done in one click (all pixels of those colors in that area marked done)
    Work unit then discarded

PDF generation:

    For a selected area, one section per color
    Each section: the area grid with that color highlighted (different symbol or bold), others shown normally
    Page 1: overview with color list and stitch counts for the area
    Colors can be reordered before generating
    Optimized for reMarkable 2 (grayscale, good square size for pen)
    Numbers used (not colors) since ~92 colors too many to distinguish visually

Workflow:

    Select area in app
    Review colors, remove rare ones or plan replacements
    Generate batch PDF
    Work on reMarkable
    Return to app, mark work unit done
    Repeat
